The paper discusses algebraic complexity theory, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that studies the computational complexity of algebraic problems. The focus is on matrix multiplication, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has applications in many areas. The paper uses geometric and representation-theoretic techniques to study the complexity of matrix multiplication, which suggests that it belongs to cs.CG (computational geometry) and cs.LG (machine learning), as well as cs.CC (computational complexity) and cs.IT (information theory). The paper also mentions applications to algebraic statistics and quantum computing, which suggest that it could also belong to cs.DS (data structures) and cs.QU (quantum physics).
